Thinking back to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have tabled a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota and vice chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That is why I am proud to present the Staff Enforcement Act, together with the civil rights body John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities for discrimination for the organisation of trade unions as for other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-union forces.
The addition of the National Labour Law Act to create a way for workers suspended for discrimination to organise a trade union representation in order to sue a civil court for justice - and to obtain damages or fines - is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks that unions have faced in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country - Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and comply with labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when that country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution to ensure that militarized autocracy, Hedki Tojos, would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions had a role to play in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that "workers" rights to unification and common bargaining and action are guaranteed. "
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Acknowledging that workers would have to organize themselves and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans added a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to form associations to secure and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
Agreements that restrict this right or aim to diminish it are zero and void; measures aimed at doing so are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to establish a trade union - and to allow that union to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - had to be protected.
Indeed, having these rights under attack in America, it is very wise to re-examine the American ideal whereby the working population must have the right to unite and be heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the working-class movement did not limit the nation's strength, but widened it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, work has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and we should do so.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representatives - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and redeemed the promise of democracy.
