The cheapest option is a waterproof point-and-shoot, such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3 + Silver Edition, both of which are available for around $300.
I took these photos at a family party with several cameras, all of which are available at a price of under $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Check your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the battery compartment and other subjects are tightly locked.
Also, adjust your camera to the photos or videos you want to capture.
Some cameras and camcorders have scene and recording modes that optimize the exposure time for the insulating underwater conditions.
And before you jump into it, check to what depth your equipment is functional.
Some cameras are only allowed for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search our shopping guide and reviews for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models.
Take multiple shots - because many won't fold.
Point-and-Shoot cameras have an LCD that lets you compose images, Action-Cams usually don't.
Even if you have an LCD, it's difficult to see this underwater, and the right image setting is a good thing.
So make a lot of shots.
If your camera has a terraced mode that makes a series of shots with slightly altered exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the further you move away from the surface.
So if possible, stay close to the surface if you're taking shots in a pool, lake or sea.
This will also allow you to put more color into your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Go close to the objects.
This is also good advice on land, but it is all the more important under water because of the poor light conditions.
It's especially important when you're working with an action cam: These devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means you need to get closer to your objects if they are to fill out the entire picture drawer.
