Putin demands Kiev start 'statehood talks' with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded Russian media reports on Sunday that the Ukrainian government is halting fighting against the separatists in the east of the country and immediately embarking on negotiations on the "statehood" of the breakaway region.
His spokesman Dimitri Peskov later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine, which is under the control of the separatists, would become a part of Russia, but that its status vis-à-vis Ukraine should be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
Putin's call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits in with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the riots began five months ago: Help for the separatists in taking territory and pressure on the Ukrainian government to allow the newly proclaimed Novorossiya region de facto independence for an alliance with Russia, rather than with the West.
In an interview with state TV channel Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign for recapturing the areas held by separatists in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were taken in March and April after Moscow annexed Ukraine's Crimea peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have lately called the captured territory "Novorossija" or "Neurusland," a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary glory of the Russian empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of campaigns by Ukrainian politicians for the elections on 26 Oct. and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in areas held by separatists, hope early peace talks are "trapped in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We need to start detailed discussions immediately, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organisation of society and the state status of south-east Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin's reference to statehood must be seen in context with the greater autonomy discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to allay fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights were at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can give the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it's not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, it's about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin's clarification of the "misinterpretation" of Putin's remarks underscored Russia's claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east, as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, on which the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are not Russians and polls from the pre-conflict period yielded a broad majority for remaining in Ukraine.
Autonomy, raised by Russian diplomats at international forums, would give Ukraine's regional governments authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area linking Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is the home port for most of Russia's navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that manufacture important components for the Russian military.
During his inauguration speech on 7 June, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko suggested that Ukrainian legislation - after new elections - should consider additions to the constitution, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and separatist rebels, whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin's latest call for Kiev to negotiate with separatist leaders on an equal footing followed a further advance by rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks entered eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
Russian-backed separatists took control of Nowoasowsk in the handover dispute, which is the first step of a campaign to take the strategic coastal region to Crimea, according to Ukrainian security officials.
That is why massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industry port with a population of 500,000, which lies between Novoasowsk and the narrow access to the Crimea Peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday and urged action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are close to a point where there is no return," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on Ukraine's territory.
The EU summit decided no concrete action, the leadership demanded the draft further sanctions against Russia, which should enter into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
